  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Increasing community resilience against Covid-19 and reducing its effects among the most vulnerable Afghan communities in Kandahar, Nimroz, and Herat Provinces</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project seeks to decrease the mortality and morbidity of Covid-19 among IDP, returnee, and host communities for people with disabilities and the most vulnerable in Herat, Kandahar, and Nimroz. It will do this by 1) Support risk communication interventions to help ensure that clear communication messaging on COVID-19 is widely available to all communities through vehicle messaging, billboards, radio spots, accessible IEC materials, SMS and other identified means, 2) Providing mental health support to affected communities through a helpline as well as providing mental health containment kits to identified families, and conducting an awareness campaign about mental health issues and Covid-19, 3) Support health facilities with both infection prevention and control materials as well as with psychosocial support and risk awareness to health facility staff For this action, gender balanced teams will be working in two districts in Herat, one district in Nimroz, and two districts in Kandahar. The action will be implemented in close coordination with other actors providing health services, as well as with other actors providing basic health and protection services in the project locations through a referral mechanism. The technical teams are supported by the Project Officer and the Data base officer within each base. The action targets health facility staff as well as at risk populations, including the women, men, girls and boys at risk of exclusion, people with disabilities, people with injuries, people experiencing psychosocial distress or mental health issues&#x2013; due to Covid-19, who are often invisible to mainstream relief organizations due to the specificity of their needs. The above interventions are aimed at reducing the vulnerability of communities to Covid-19, and increasing the capacity to respond whilst reinforcing positive coping mechanisms</narrative>
  </description>
